Diagnosis.
The species can be recognized by its humeri being distinctly produced but relatively short and broad, apically obtuse, directed slightly posterolaterad, punctured, and tinged with reddish. The male (
Figs 1–3
) and female (
Fig. 45
) terminalia are diagnostic.

Male and female terminalia. Male
. Genital capsule (
Figs 1–3
) with a pair of short posterolateral projections each with a dense tuft of setae apically; dorsal rim broadly U-shaped; ventral rim with a tuft of setae medially, ventral infolding densely pilose. Paramere (
Figs 20–21
) L-shaped, apex finger-shaped. 
Female
(
Fig. 45
). Posterior margin with a deep, shield-shaped median incision surrounding valvifers VIII; posterior margin of laterotergites VIII prominent, far surpassing posterolateral angle of abdominal segment VII. Pendergrast’s organs on ventrites VI and VII broadly separeted, those on ventrite VII much smaller than those on ventrite VI.
